## `As400WorkingRelationshipRequest`

This is the most important class to update.

Use a `Set` instead of a `List` so duplicate values are removed during deserialization:

```java
@Data
@NoArgsConstructor
@AllArgsConstructor
@Builder
public class As400WorkingRelationshipRequest {

    @NotEmpty
    @JsonProperty("relationship_types")
    private Set<String> relationshipTypes;

    @NotBlank
    private String status;
}
```

Then this input:

```json
"relationship_types": [
  "DEALER",
  "SELLER",
  "ZONE_MANAGER",
  "DEALER"
]
```

becomes:

```java
["DEALER", "SELLER", "ZONE_MANAGER"]
```

internally.

Use `LinkedHashSet` if preserving JSON order matters:

```java
@Builder.Default
@JsonProperty("relationship_types")
private Set<String> relationshipTypes =
        new LinkedHashSet<>();
```

## Better: use enums for controlled values

String fields work, but enums are safer.

### `RelationshipType`

```java
public enum RelationshipType {
    SELLER,
    DEALER,
    ZONE_MANAGER
}
```

Then:

```java
@NotEmpty
@JsonProperty("relationship_types")
private Set<RelationshipType> relationshipTypes;
```

Your service loop becomes:

```java
for (RelationshipType relationshipType
        : workingRelationship.getRelationshipTypes()) {

    String relationshipTypeValue =
            relationshipType.name();

    // repository lookup and mapping
}
```

### `WorkingRelationshipStatus`

```java
public enum WorkingRelationshipStatus {
    ACTIVE,
    INACTIVE
}
```

Then:

```java
@NotNull
private WorkingRelationshipStatus status;
```

### `SourceRecordType`

```java
public enum SourceRecordType {
    SELLER,
    DEALER,
    ZONE_MANAGER
}
```

Then in `As400SourceRequest`:

```java
@NotNull
@JsonProperty("source_record_type")
private SourceRecordType sourceRecordType;
```

This prevents unsupported values such as:

```json
"source_record_type": "something-random"
```

from reaching the service.

## Recommended final model

I would use:

```java
Set<RelationshipType>
SourceRecordType
WorkingRelationshipStatus
Instant snapshotTimestamp
```

but keep AS400 person status as a `String` for now:

```java
private String status;
```

because it contains source-specific codes such as `"40"` rather than your internal enum values.

## Service changes required after using enums

Current code:

```java
for (String relationshipType
        : workingRelationship.getRelationshipTypes()) {
```

becomes:

```java
for (RelationshipType relationshipType
        : workingRelationship.getRelationshipTypes()) {

    String relationshipTypeValue =
            relationshipType.name();

    Optional<PersonSalesPointRelationshipEntity>
            existingRelationship =
            relationshipRepository
                    .findByPersonUserIdAndSalesPointIdAndRelationshipType(
                            user.getUserId(),
                            salesPoint.getSalesPointId(),
                            relationshipTypeValue
                    );

    PersonSalesPointRelationshipEntity relationship =
            existingRelationship.orElseGet(
                    PersonSalesPointRelationshipEntity::new
            );

    boolean relationshipChanged =
            updateRelationship(
                    relationship,
                    user,
                    salesPoint,
                    relationshipTypeValue,
                    workingRelationship
            );

    relationshipRepository.save(relationship);

    anyRelationshipCreated |=
            existingRelationship.isEmpty();

    anyRelationshipChanged |=
            relationshipChanged;
}
```

And inside `updateRelationship(...)`:

```java
relationship.setStatus(
        workingRelationship.getStatus().name()
);
```

The strongest version is therefore:

```java
private Set<RelationshipType> relationshipTypes;
private WorkingRelationshipStatus status;
```

That keeps the incoming contract aligned with the JSON and reduces validation logic inside `UserSynchronizationService`.
